'''David Allen Gaines''' (December 30, 1947–January 11, 1988) was an American environmentalist and the founder of the [[Mono Lake Committee]].<ref name="MongilloBooth2001">{{cite book|editor1=John F. Mongillo|editor2=Bibi Booth|contribution=David Gaines (1947–1988)| author=Mono Lake Committee|title=Environmental Activists|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=n42Rf_ibaMcC&pg=PA104|year=2001|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-313-30884-0|pages=104–106}}</ref> &nbsp;His main goal in accomplishing a lawsuit was to work with the opposition ([[Los Angeles Department of Water and Power]]) instead of demonizing the organization, this ultimately got them ahead.  He and his wife, Sally Gaines, began the committee in 1978.  They required help from students at [[Stanford University]], [[University of California, Davis|UC Davis]], [[University of California, Santa Cruz|UC Santa Cruz]], and [[Earlham College]].  From the information he collected he co-wrote a chapter in the book ''California Riparian Systems''.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.nz/books?id=UhjbO_CC_VoC&source=gbs_navlinks_s|chapterurl=https://books.google.co.nz/books?id=UhjbO_CC_VoC&pg=PA528&source=gbs_toc_r&cad=4#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=California Riparian Systems: Ecology, Conservation, and Productive Management|chapter=Destruction of Riparian Systems Due to Water Development in the Mono Lake|editor-last=Warner|editor-first=Richard E.|editor-last2=Hendrix|editor-first2=Kathleen M.|last=Stine|first=Scott|last2=Gaines|first2=David|last3=Vorster|first3=Peter|pages=528-533|date=1984|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=9780520050358|language=en}}</ref>  This got scientist engaged to help.  As a collaborative team, The Mono Lake Committee took a stand against LADWP.

He died on January 11, 1988 in a car accident caused by a wind storm.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Stammer|first1=Larrry B.|title=Obituaries:  Crash on Sierra Highway Kills Mono Lake Activist|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1988-01-12/news/mn-35137_1_mono-lake-committee|website=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=23 May 2017|date=12 January 1988}}</ref> Sally and his kids, Vireo and Sage, survived the accident.

