The '''Environmental Media Association''' ('''EMA''') is a non-profit organization which was founded in 1989 by Cindy and [[Alan Horn]] and Lyn and [[Norman Lear]]. EMA works with the entertainment industry to encourage green production and raise the public's environmental awareness.<ref name="ema-online1">[http://www.ema-online.org/about_us.php About Us - Environmental Media Association]</ref> The group provides a "Green Seal" to productions which reduce their environmental footprint.<ref>[http://www.ema-online.org/green_seal.php About EMA Green Seal - Environmental Media Association]</ref> The first movie to have the EMA Green Seal in its credits was [[The Incredible Hulk (film)|The Incredible Hulk]], which made specific efforts during its 2007 [[The Incredible Hulk (film)#Filming|filming]] to cut carbon emissions and waste created during production.<ref>[http://www.ecorazzi.com/2008/06/13/hulk-to-be-first-movie-with-ema-green-seal-in-credits/ 'Hulk' To Be First Movie With EMA Green Seal In Credits &#124; Ecorazzi &#124; Ecorazzi]</ref> There are also various TV episodes, such as the ''[[Futurama]]'' episode "The Problem with Popplers", and various movies have been awarded the Environmental Media Award, which is awarded to the best television show or film with an environmental message.
EMA also hosts the annual [[Environmental Media Awards]],<ref name="ema-online1">[http://www.ema-online.org/about_us.php About Us - Environmental Media Association]</ref> an awards ceremony which celebrates the entertainment industry’s environmental efforts.
