{{update|date=September 2015}} [[File:Mies van der Rohe gas station.jpeg|thumb|The filling station, in 2007.]] [[File:Station essence Ile des Soeurs - Mies.jpg|thumb|The filling station, closed, in April 2010.]] The '''Nun's Island gas station''' was a [[modern architecture|modernist-style]] [[filling station]] designed by [[Ludwig Mies van der Rohe]] in 1969, one of four buildings by Mies in [[Nuns' Island]], an island in the city of [[Montreal]]. It is no longer a working gas station after being converted to a [[community centre]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ville.montreal.qc.ca/portal/page?_pageid=2480,2899876&_dad=portal&_schema=PORTAL |title=In Your Neighbourhood: The Mies Van Der Rohe Buildings |accessdate=2008-03-24 |work=City of Montreal Web site }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/servlet/story/RTGAM.20090127.wstation27/BNStory/National/|title=The Ritz of gas stations looks for a new life|last=Perreaux|first=Les|date=2009-01-27|work=[[The Globe and Mail]]|accessdate=2009-01-28}}</ref>
It was the first gas station on the island, and the first designed by Mies, who had worked in collaboration with local architect [[Paul H. Lapointe]] on the project. The station was commissioned by [[Imperial Oil]].<ref name="Mies gas">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=9aUtAAAAIBAJ&sjid=5J8FAAAAIBAJ&pg=2948,4865305&dq=montreal+architect&hl=en|title=Master architect designs unique station|date="Both pavilions use geothermal energy for heating and air conditioning," 20, 1968|work=Montreal Gazette|pages=90|accessdate=26 December 2009}}</ref>
==Community centre== [[File:La station.png|thumbnail|"La Station" lighting at night]] The borough of [[Verdun, Quebec|Verdun]] transformed the building into a [[community arts]] centre, '''La Station'''.<ref name="LEJTENYI">{{cite news|url=http://www.montrealmirror.com/2009/031909/news2.html|title=Nuns saves Mies|last=Lejtenyi|first=Patrick|work=[[Montreal Mirror]]|publisher=Communications Gratte-Ciel Ltée|accessdate=26 December 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606092531/http://www.montrealmirror.com/2009/031909/news2.html#|archive-date=2011-06-06|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref> [[Eric Gauthier (architect)|Eric Gauthier]] was the lead architect on the project, which saw the two glass pavilions rebuilt to their original 3,000- and {{convert|1,000|sqft|m2|adj=on}} sizes.<ref name=Leblanc>{{cite news|last=Leblanc|first=Dave|title=Mies's Montreal gas station gets new lease on life|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/life/home-and-garden/architecture/dave-leblanc/miess-montreal-gas-station-gets-new-lease-on-life/article2089835/|accessdate=8 July 2011|newspaper=[[The Globe and Mail]]|date=8 July 2011}}</ref>
'''La Station''' is a community centre for teens and people over 50 years of age. The two main buildings are called the ''salle blanche'' (English: white room) and ''salle noire'' (English: black room), after their floor colours. The original glass-enclosed attendant's booth serves as a display case of Mies' and the building's history, with the former [[fuel dispenser]]s marked by ventilation shafts. The centre uses [[geothermal energy]].<ref name=Woolfrey>{{cite news|last=Woolfrey|first=John|title=LA STATION: THE JEWEL IN THE NUNS' ISLAND CROWN|url=http://montreal.openfile.ca/montreal/text/la-station-jewel-nuns%E2%80%99-island-crown-0|accessdate=26 February 2012|newspaper=Openfile Montreal|date=24 February 2012}}{{dead link|date=February 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>
